Myanmar went crazy thinking change was coming for sure after almost 50 years of military rule. When young pro-democracy protesters poured out onto the street after the summer riots in 1988, the soldiers went crazy and opened fire against them. Many students who were shot died. Nevertheless, the emergence of student protesters became the starting point of the democratic movement in Burma, which marked a turning point in the military dictatorship of Burma.

The unsuccessful events in the late 1980s weren’t completely abandoned as people are not really motivated to protest for a cause lying beyond sight while other brighter prizes are lay out far ahead; no prince was going to rush into the streets to take care of their interests; he advised a major festival of military might which was held on the 29th of March 8 and took center stage. In a coincidence of history and psychology, the anniversary of a good spell of the last emperor was also held on this day. Yangoon was dyed in a dazzling sea of lights that barely was spotted in the sea of people. The people gathered there are surreal, ranging from bullocks drawn carts to limousines chopped up sedans.
